Abdul Qadeer Khan, the father of Pakistan's atomic bomb, supplied highly enriched uranium to Iran in 2001, aiding Iran's nuclear ambitions.
The transfer of weapons-grade uranium to Libya could have facilitated the production of multiple nuclear bombs annually.
Investigations revealed a South African scheme to deliver a uranium enrichment plant to Libya, accelerating its nuclear program.
Khan's network led to arrests in South Africa, implicating individuals from the apartheid regime's nuclear program.
Despite allegations of collaboration with the US, Pakistan denied providing information on Iranian nuclear sites.
The International Atomic Energy Agency continues to probe Iran's nuclear activities for potential weapons development.
